\maketitle

I have tried to follow all of the referee's suggestions (I am very grateful to them for their careful reading of the manuscript, their precise comments, and their quick response). The changes that I would like to underline are the following:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=.5cm]
 \item Points 6 and 35. In Remark 2.3, I have sketched a proof of the classification result of \S 2 via meromorphic differentials. Since the proof via the conductor ideal was explained at length in case $(1,1,0)$ and only rushed through in case $(1,0,1)$, I have chosen to discuss the alternative proof in the latter. Personally, I do not find this proof much easier, but it is possible that I am missing a simpler argument; certainly, the reader will benefit from a parallel presentation of the two methods. I have moved the description of the dualising line bundle from \S 4 to \S 2 (Corollary 2.5).
 
 \item Points 7, 11, 24 and 70. I have corrected the assumptions on the base characteristic. Now, footnote 2 on p.11 points out what we need to perform the coordinate change on the normalisation. Remark 3.3 clarifies the jump in automorphisms/crimping spaces when $\operatorname{char}(\mathbf k)=2$.
 
 \item\label{S4} Points 31, 34, 44, etc. I have rewritten most of \S 4 on the classification of semistable tails. Now, the proof is explained in terms of the existence of a certain piecewise linear function on the tropicalization of the curve. Even though I have made the statement of Proposition 4.8 less explicit than it used to be, I hope that it gained in clarity, thanks to the new language in which it is formulated. I have added two preliminary paragraphs to \S 4, one on admissible covers (with a formal definition and a classical theorem, complementing the examples that I already had), and one on piecewise-linear functions on the tropicalization of logarithmic curves.
 
 \item Point 58, etc. As a consequence of \eqref{S4}, I have completely rewritten the existence part of the valuative criterion of properness. Again, I feel that this new point of view makes it much cleaner.
 
\end{enumerate}

